@page "/safety"
<SeoHead Title="Safety and Trust" Description="The local-first, review-first and fail-closed boundaries behind LifeOS." CanonicalPath="/safety" />
<PageIntro Eyebrow="Safety & Trust" Title="Useful systems should make their boundaries obvious." Summary="LifeOS is designed around local ownership, visible review, honest unavailable states and evidence-backed release decisions." />
<section class="page-shell section"><div class="principle-grid"><article><span>01</span><h2>Local-first</h2><p>Private Desktop and Companion records are not published by this Website. Public content is a separate, sanitized surface.</p></article><article><span>02</span><h2>Review-first</h2><p>Consequential operations should be inspectable and confirmable. Status never relies on colour alone.</p></article><article><span>03</span><h2>Fail-closed</h2><p>When a real handling path is missing, the feature remains visibly unavailable instead of pretending a submission succeeded.</p></article></div></section>
<section class="page-shell section"><div class="boundary-table"><div class="boundary-head"><span>Boundary</span><span>What LifeOS does</span><span>What it does not claim</span></div><div><strong>Website</strong><span>Static-first public product information and sanitized proof.</span><span>Access to private local records or a hidden portal.</span></div><div><strong>Automation</strong><span>Guarded execution with visible readiness and review conditions.</span><span>Unbounded autonomous authority.</span></div><div><strong>Evidence</strong><span>Tests, screenshots, scans, releases and defect verification.</span><span>That a screenshot alone proves every safety property.</span></div><div><strong>Early Access</strong><span>A clearly disabled preview until storage and privacy handling exist.</span><span>That personal details are being collected now.</span></div></div></section>
